Disk Forensics > [T2]: Extracting Time zone

(3) Time zone

You can determine the system's timezone using the following registry key:

SYSTEM\ControlSet001\Control\TimeZoneInformation

 

Timezone - (zoom in)

  • TimeZoneInformation key
  • TimeZoneInformation key path
  • 'Bias' field contains the difference between the local time set on the system and UTC in minutes stored in 32-bit unsigned format. You can decode it using RegistryExplorer's "Data Interpreter". In the previous figure,  the 'Bias' value is "4294967176", which equates to "-120" minutes when decoded. That means UTC is two hours (120 minutes) ahead of the local set timezone.
  • 'TimeZoneKeyName' contains the time zone name of the local system.

 

Some users can change their systems' time zone. Fortunately, the registry keeps track of when was the last time a registry key was updated and stores it in a field called 'Last Write Time'. This information is not viewable in Regedit and can be seen either by exporting the key to a text file and checking the "last write time" or using tools like Registry Explorer, as shown below.

By inspecting the last write time to the "TimeZoneInformation" registry key, you can identify when was the last time the time zone changed. This is an important piece of information because each log timestamp will use the timezone set when this log was created.

 

Viewing Last write time using registry explorer - (zoom in)


One important thing to note is that registry timestamps use the UTC timezone (+0), while windows event logs use the machine's local time zone, so make sure to base your analysis on the same timezone. Let's look at the following example.

Change your computer name and check this change timestamp in both registry and Windows event logs. The following two screenshots belong to the same event. You can see that the registry timestamp is "10:50" while the event log timestamp is "12:50", which is two hours ahead (the computer's local timezone is +2).

 

ComputerName key last write time displayed in UTC - (zoom in)

 

Computer name update event displayed in local time zone - (zoom in)
